8.title: Pink Eye
dlg:
This inflammation or infection causes blood vessels in these areas to become more pronounced and so the whites of your eyes take a pink or red color.

What caused this inflammation?

It might be virus, bacteria, allergy , chemicals, contact lenses or trauma.

0.header:
This is inflammation or infection of the thin, transparent film that lines the eyeball or eyelids.

Let's see what you need to do and how best to take care of this.

1.header:
the first question you would ask yourself if the eye is inflamed is:

"Does this look like pink eye?"

Let's start with that.

We will take a look at your symptoms and see if you are looking at pink eye, what type of pink eye and what is the best course of action to take.

2.header:
the first question you would ask yourself if the eye is inflamed is:

"Does this look like pink eye?"

Let's start with that.

We will take a look at your symptoms and see if you are looking at pink eye, what type of pink eye and what is the best course of action to take.

3.header:
Hmmm.
Well, a lot of things including pink eye can cause that. So let's Continue.

4.header: Are you experiencing increased tearing in the eye?

5.header:
Just thinking.
Other things including pink eye can also cause this. Let's continue and see if you can narrow it down.

6.header: Is the eye itchy and red?

7.header:
Alright.
This is a symptom of pink eye. In some cases, the eyes will be itchy and red.

Symptoms of pink eye include:

  • A feeling of something in the eye
  • Increased tearing
  • Eye is itchy and red.

8.header: Is the eye or eyelid swollen and sore?

9.header:
Yes?
This can be a symptom of a pink eye infection.

Symptoms of pink eye include:

  • A feeling of something in the eye
  • Increased tearing
  • Eye is itchy and red.
  • Swollen and sore eye or eyelid.

10.header: Any crusted eyelash in the morning?

11.header:
Yes?
This can be a symptom of pink eye.

Symptoms of pink eye include:

  • A feeling of something in the eye
  • Increased tearing
  • Eye is itchy and red.
  • Swollen and sore eye or eyelid
  • Crusted eyelash in the morning.

12.header: What about a hazy or blurred vision due to mucus or pus?

13.header:
This is a symptom of pinkeye infection.

Symptoms of pinkeye include:

  • A feeling of something in the eye
  • Increased tearing
  • Eye is itchy and red.
  • Swollen and sore eye or eyelid
  • Crusted eyelash in the morning
  • Hazy or blurred vision due to mucus or pus.

14.header:
Alright.
Those were symptoms of a pink eye inflammation or infection.

If most of those symptoms apply to you, then you may be looking at a pink eye.

If none apply to you, you may not be looking at a pink eye infection.

Let's continue and see what type of pink eye you are looking at.

20.header:
Is this viral, bacterial or allergy related pink eye?

Note that there are other causes of pink eye such as using contact lenses, irritants and so on.

Let's see what type you may be looking at.

21.header: Is the discharge coming from the eye watery?

23.header: Are you noticing a thick pus coming from the eye(s)?

24.header:
Pus?
If there is pus, suspect pink eye of bacterial origin.

Let's continue and see if this is the case to the best of our knowledge.

Keep in mind that differentiating between viral and bacterial infectious conjunctivitis is not highly accurate. Not even in the doctor's office.

25.header: Is this thick pus yellowish and/or greenish in color?

26.header:
Yes?
Suspect a bacteria related pink eye.

27.header: Are both eyes affected or is it mainly one eye that is pink or red?

28.header:
One eye?
Suspect a bacteria related pink eye.

Bacteria related pink eye more often would affect just one eye or start with one eye being infected before spreading to the other.

Whereas viral or allergy related pink eye more often affect both eyes.

29.header:
These symptoms often goes with bacterial compared to the viral pink eye.

Bacterial-like symptoms include:

  • Pus
  • Thick discharge
  • Yellowish and/or greenish discharge.
  • Often affects just one eye
  • Eyelids get stuck together in the morning.

Now, if this is the case with you, you have to give the doctor a call or seek urgent care. There is no antibiotic over-the-counter to take care of bacteria related pink eye.

Once again keep in mind that differentiating between viral and bacterial pink eye is not accurate. Not even in the doctor's office.

Would you like to see the nearest urgent care clinic to you if you suspect it is bacterial or Continue?

Continuing for now will assume a viral or allergy related pink eye and there is no thick pus.

30.header:
Think viral or allergic conjunctivitis if it is just watery and no thick pus or discharge.

In most cases, with bacterial conjunctivitis, you will come across thick pus oozing from the eye. This is not usually the case with viral or allergy related conjunctivitis.

Also bacterial related pink eye more often affect just one eye. But viral or allergy related more often affect both eyes at the same time.

Well, let's see if it is viral or allergy related pink eye. This will assume it is not bacteria related.

31.header: Does it feel as if there is a foreign object in the eye?

32.header:
Yes?
Suspect a viral related pink eye in that case.

With viral conjunctivitis, it would feel as if there is something in the eye.

Suspect viral related pink eye if feeling something in the eye does not include sneezing, running nose or other allergy related symptoms.

33.header:
Are your eyes very itchy?

Or burning?

34.header:
Yes?
You might start suspecting allergic conjunctivitis.

Viral conjunctivitis usually do not include itching of the eye, at least not intensely.

35.header:
Did your eyes get red very quickly?

And puffy?

36.header:
Yes?
You may be looking at a pink eye due to allergy.

Usually, the eye get red pretty fast in allergic conjunctivitis. If there are other symptoms like runny nose or sneezing, then you should be looking at allergy related pink eye.

Would you like to see the allergy section or Continue with pink eye?

37.header:
Alright.
We tried to see what type of conjunctivitis you may be looking at.

Why is this important?

It would help you determine if you need to see a doctor as soon as possible or if you can probably ride it out.

Example, if it is bacteria related, you must seek urgent care. There is nothing over the counter to take care of that. So don't waste you time or money on over-the-counter eye drops.

Note that pink eye is very contagious if it is viral or bacterial related. You must wash your hands after touching the eye and avoid sharing towel or pillows for now.

Let's see if you need to see a doctor right away or do you think you should seek urgent care from the discussion so far?

40.header: Can you can ride this out or do you need to see a doctor?

42.header: Do you also have moderate to severe pain in the eye(s)

43.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need further evaluation to rule out infection of the cornea.
  • Meanwhile apply a cold compress to help with the pain.

44.header: Do you think you are looking at a bacteria type pink eye?

45.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May need antibiotic eye drops.
  • No antibiotics eyedrops for this over-the-counter.

46.header: Do you also have double vision, or see halos around things.

47.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need professional evaluation.
  • May be something else going on.

48.header:
OK. Has this been going on for 3 or more days?

And no improvement?

49.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to prevent secondary bacteria infection.

50.header: Is the eye(s) swollen and bringing out pus?

51.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible bacteria infection.
  • Meanwhile apply a warm compress for now.

52.header:
Infectious pink eye is contagious.

Because infectious pink eye is contagious, we recommend you see a doctor. Especially so if you have other people in the house. If it is just you, you may be able to ride this out if is not a bacterial type.

If you don't think you need to see a doctor, let's see what a pharmacist recommend you do that may be available over-the-counter.

Would you like to do this or see the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

9.title: Red Eye
dlg:
This could have been caused by a lot of things from conjunctivitis to sun exposure, dusts to name a few.
It could also have resulted from something very serious that will need urgent or emergency care.

Sometimes called CLARE (Contact lens acute red eye), this type of keratitis is often bacterial and you will need antibiotic eye drops urgently. How urgent, see it as bacteria invading your eyes. They spread very fast. The more you delay, the more bacteria is going to colonize the eye and do more damage. So hurry to the nearest urgent care clinic.

0.header:
A red eye may be due to dilation of blood vessels in the eye's surface.

Let's rule out anything that require urgent or emergency care before seeing what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter for red eye relief.

1.header: Did this redness of the eye start after a sudden severe eye pain?

3.header:
Yes?
Let's make sure you are not looking at an emergency situation like glaucoma.

5.header: Are you also experiencing headache with this eye pain and redness?

6.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • These are main symptoms of acute angle glaucoma.

Would you like to see the nearest hospital or Continue?

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

7.header: Are you having a decreased or blurred vision with this red eye and eye pain?

8.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • This is a symptom of acute angle glaucoma

Would you like to see the nearest hospital or Continue?

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

9.header: What about getting confused with this redness of the eyes and eye pain?

10.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • This is a symptom of acute angle glaucoma

Would you like to see the nearest hospital or Continue?

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

11.header: Are you also seeing colored rainbows or halos around lights?

12.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • This is a major symptom of glaucoma

Would you like to see the nearest hospital or Continue?

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

13.header: Are you experiencing nausea and/or vomiting with this red eye and eye pain?

14.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • This is a major symptom of acute angle glaucoma.

Would you like to see the nearest hospital or Continue?

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

15.header:
Those were the main symptoms of acute angle closure glaucoma.

This require emergency room visit if they applied to you.

Discuss glaucoma (national eye institute)

If this does not apply to you, let's continue and rule out other things that causes redness of the eyes that be dangerous.

20.header: With the redness, is the eye so painful you have difficulty opening the eyelid?

21.header:
Yes?
Let's make sure we are not looking at something like keratitis.

22.header: Are you seeing increased sensitivity to light?

23.header:
Yes?
This is a sign and symptom of keratitis.

24.header: What about a feeling of something in the eye?

25.header:
Yes?
Keratitis sometimes cause a feeling that something is in the eye.

26.header: Are you seeing floaters with this red eyes?

27.header:
Yes?
This can be a sign and symptom of keratitis.

28.header:
Is your vision decreasing with this redness of the eye?

Or getting blurry?

29.header:
Yes?
This is one of the symptoms of keratitis.

30.header:
OK.
We just went through the symptoms of keratitis which require urgent care.

Expand more on keratitis and advice to seek urgent care

If this does not apply to you, let's continue.

40.header: Are you looking at rusting or flaking of the eyelids / eyelashes?

41.header:
Yes?
Let's make sure you are not looking at Blepharitis.

42.header:
Do you feel a gritty sensation in the eyes?

Like there is something in the eye?

44.header: What about a burning sensation?

46.header: Are the eyes producing a lot of tears?

48.header:
Are the eyelids margins red and swollen?

And itchy?

50.header:
Do you see crusted eyelashes upon awakening?

Or eyelids that look greasy?

51.header:
Yes?
This is a sign and symptom of blepharitis.

52.header:
We just went through the symptoms of blepharitis.

Discuss blepharitis briefly.

If you suspect you may be looking at blepharitis, call the doctor for a complete evaluation.

If that is not the case, then let's continue and rule something else out.

60.header:
With this red eye, are you having a gritty feeling of something in the eye?

Always wanting to rub the eye(s)?

61.header:
Yes?
Let's make sure you are not looking at a conjunctivitis or pink eye.

62.header: Does the eye(s) look swollen or inflammed?

63.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of pink eye.

Swelling of the conjunctiva (the thin layer that lines the white part of the eye and the inside of the eyelid) is common with pink eye.

64.header: Any watery or mucus discharge with this red eye(s)?

65.header:
Yes?
You may be looking at a pink eye.

Would you like to see the entry for pink eye or Continue?

66.header:
What about crusting of the eyelids or eyelashes?

Especially in the morning?

67.header:
Yes?
You may be looking at a pink eye inflammation.

Would you like to see our entry for pink eye for a more detailed discussion or Continue?

68.header:
Is the eye(s) itching and tearing with this redness?

Also burning?

69.header:
Yes?
You may be looking at a pink eye inflammation.

70.header: Is the eye getting more sensitive to light?

72.header:
{{firstname}}
Those were symptoms of a pink eye infection.

Pink eye is very contagious, so if you suspect you are experiencing one, see our entry on pink eye for a more detailed analysis so you can make the best decision on what to do.

If you don't think so, then let's continue.

80.header: Do you feel eye pain especially when opening or closing the eye?

81.header:
Yes?
Hope we are not looking at a scratched cornea. Let's take a look.

82.header: Did you say earlier that it feels as if there is sand or grit in the eye?

83.header:
Yes?
We may be looking at a scratched cornea. This is a sign and symptom.

84.header: Did you also say the eye is getting very sensitive to light?

85.header:
Yes?
This frequently happens with a scratched cornea.

86.header:
Alright. Is your vision getting very blurry?

A lot of tearing too.

87.header:
OK
A cornea abrasion or scratched cornea can cause this.

Symptoms of a scratched cornea include:

  • Feeling like sand in the eye
  • Eye pain when you open or close the eye
  • Tearing
  • Sensitivity to light
  • Blurred vision

88.header:
We just went through the symptoms of a scratched cornea.

If you suspect you may be looking at a scratched cornea, go to the nearest urgent care center or hospital. Do not attempt to wait it out. It is very painful and would get worse with time.

You don't know how bad the scratch is and severe complications can develop. Know that the signs and symptoms of a cornea abrasion may not show up until later. So you won't know when you poked the eye or had the incident that scratched the cornea.

If you are experiencing severe eye pain, seek urgent care. Else let's continue.

100.header: Do you use contacts and now your eyes are red?

101.header:
Yes?
Keratitis is a major complication with using contact lenses.

If you are looking at symptoms listed below, seek urgent care immediately.

It could be bacterial, viral, or fungal. It can lead to corneal scarring that impairs vision, and may lead to the need for a cornea transplant.

Symptoms include:

  • Eye pain (often sudden)
  • Reduced vision
  • Increased light sensitivity
  • Excessive tearing or discharge from the eyes
  • Feelings of scratching each time he or she blinks the eye

102.header:
With the red eyes, do you also have runny nose, sneezing and watery eyes?

Also itchy eyes?

103.header:
Probably mainly looking at an allergy related red eyes.

Would you like to see what we have prepared regarding seasonal allergy or Continue?

104.header:
If none of the discussions apply to you so far, you may not need to seek urgent care.

You may be looking at a minor eye irritation or subconjunctival hemorrhage

Subconjunctival hemorrhage is like a bruise of the eye or a broken blood vessel on the surface of the eye.

It usually appears as a single, concentrated spot of red, or many scattered red splotches, on the white of the eye. The redness is blood under the conjunctiva.

Treatment of a subconjunctival hemorrhage is generally not necessary. Over time, the blood spot will slowly disappear, clearing up on its own. This may take days or weeks.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend to help get rid of this red eye that is available over-the-counter.

10.title: Sty
dlg: Also an infected hair follicle of the eyelash can cause a red bump at the base of the eyelash , under or inside the eyelid. Then you will be looking at a sty(e). There are other reasons to develop a stye.

0.header:
Sty(e) may result from oil glands of the eyelid becoming clogged and infected.

Let's see if it is a sty you are looking at. For instance, how do you know it is not an insect bite or allergy or something more serious?

1.header:
Look at the mirror.
Is there a bump or pimple in the corner...

... or any other area of the eyelid?

It could also be just below or above the eyelid.

2.header:
None?
OK. Is there any kind of swelling on the eyelid?

3.header:
NO?
Oh well, this may not be a sty you are experiencing.

We will recommend you check out the other eye conditions we have listed and see which symptoms closely match what you are experiencing.

Would you like to continue or check out the nearest urgent care medical center to you?

Continuing would assume you are looking at some kind of swelling on the eyelid.

4.header: Does this swelling look like a pimple?

6.header: Is the swelling painful and/or itchy?

7.header:
No?
Well, if you think you are looking at a sty, let's continue.

We will assume you are looking at a bump or pimple from here forward.

8.header:
OK.
Let's continue and see if you are looking at a stye and figure out what to do about it.
